    frontmatter: {"title":"Notes on writing our own MDX compiler","date":"2026-04-21","author":"matheus","description":"Why we didn't just use Next.js's MDX loader, and what we learned building a pipeline on top of @vertz/mdx.","slug":"compiler-notes","tags":["compiler","framework"],"draft":false},
    html: "<h2 id=\"why-write-a-loader\">Why write a loader</h2>\n<p>Every framework&#39;s MDX integration is a compromise. Each one couples the\nparser, the JSX runtime, and the deployment target in a way that&#39;s hard to\nswap out later. <code>@vertz/mdx</code> keeps the unified pipeline configurable so a\nblog, a docs site, or a cookbook can all plug into the same parser with\ndifferent runtimes.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-pipeline-in-one-picture\">The pipeline in one picture</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><code>@mdx-js/mdx</code> parses the source into a hast tree.</li>\n<li><code>@shikijs/rehype</code> syntax-highlights fenced code blocks.</li>\n<li>A rehype slug injector assigns stable ids to h2 / h3.</li>\n<li>A tiny JSX shim serializes the tree into an HTML string.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2 id=\"what-we-gave-up\">What we gave up</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>No dynamic component overrides at the MDX layer (deferred to Phase 4).</li>\n<li>The body renders through <code>innerHTML</code>, not JSX — hydration is static.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"what-we-kept\">What we kept</h2>\n<p><code>@vertz/mdx</code>&#39;s <code>compileMdx()</code> remains the single source of truth for\nfrontmatter parsing. The blog just adds a second pass to produce the\nstring output.</p>",
